The paper deals with pseudorandom generators and derandomization, which are central topics in computational complexity theory (cs.CC). It also involves the analysis of pseudorandomness and randomness-efficient algorithms, which are relevant to cryptography (cs.CR) and information theory (cs.IT). The use of switching lemmas and families of circuits suggests a connection to circuit complexity (cs.DS), while the optimization of seed lengths involves probabilistic and statistical techniques (cs.LG).
